    "body": "@Giulio2002 <https://github.com/Giulio2002> How does it help to be salty?\nWe are all using erigon for a reason and think it’s superior. But does this\nmean there cannot be simple but powerful suggestions to make it even better?\nBeing as old as it already is, erigon can easily adapt at least documenting\nbreaking changes. Nobody asks for no breaking changes at all. We understand\nthat being able to introduce breaking changes keeps you more agile.\nBut to be honest, the approach of telling people \"it’s alpha software, fuck\noff\" led to Nethermind overtaking erigon quite impressively. Keep it up if\nthat’s your goal.\n\nOn Tue, 23 May 2023 at 21:33, Dylan Caponi ***@***.***> wrote:\n\n> @Giulio2002 <https://github.com/Giulio2002> I like Erigon and want to\n> help it improve. This is why I'm going to the effort of providing\n> constructive criticism. What do you hope to achieve by pushing away users?\n>\n> —\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/ledgerwatch/erigon/issues/6077#issuecomment-1560086724>,\n> or unsubscribe\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/ACWUTTP2CX34Y25UWD2BQLTXHUNHRANCNFSM6AAAAAASEAN2HE>\n> .\n> You are receiving this because you commented.Message ID:\n> ***@***.***>\n>\n",
